From M.Huck at derby.ac.uk  Mon Sep  8 10:29:56 2014
From: M.Huck at derby.ac.uk (Maren Huck)
Date: Mon, 8 Sep 2014 09:29:56 +0100
Subject: [R-sig-eco] LSCV and hlim
Message-ID: <0E1E893FE7447F4F883C415B21D0E5E9012BEC097387@MKT-MBX01.university.ds.derby.ac.uk>

Dear All,

I think I have a problem understanding the meaning of hlim when calculating the kernel bandwidth using LSCV. I would very much appreciating if anybody has some good suggestions.
 As I understood the help page, the LSCV would be searched within the limits of "ranging from hlim[1]*href to hlim[2]*href". So if the href is for example 23.7, I would expect that under the default setting where hlim is defined to be c(0.1,1.5) my LSCV-h would be estimated to be somewhere between 2.37 and 47.4.
With my dataset (sorry, not attached, since I am not sure how to), I get 3.7 (using the default limits of c(0.1,1.5)). So far so good, although this gives a ridiculously small home-range.
If I now play around with the limits I can get very different values, e.g.,
> udLSCV<- kernelUD(E500sp, h="LSCV", hlim = c(0.001, 10))
> udLSCV at h$h        
[1] 4.811839

> udLSCV<- kernelUD(E500sp, h="LSCV", ,hlim = c(0.001, 100))
> udLSCV at h$h        
[1] 23.96653

> udLSCV<- kernelUD(E500sp, h="LSCV", ,hlim = c(0.001, 1000))
> udLSCV at h$h        
[1] 239.4542

If LSCV "forces" me to play around with these limits to get a home-range that "looks" sensible, what is the point of using a supposedly more "objective" estimator, rather than using some rule-of-thumb or user-defined method (e.g., Schuler, K. L., G. M. Schroeder, J. A. Jenks, and J. G. Kie. 2013. Ad-hoc smoothing parameter performance in kernel estimates of GPS-derived home ranges. Wildlife Biology. In press.)?
Or is there also an "objective" way on how to decide on reasonable limits for LSCV to get a reasonable home-range?

Thanks in advance for any suggestions,
Maren

Maren

